WEBVTT

00:03.018 --> 00:08.105
I'm interviewing Dr. Donald McDonald, head of the 
Department of Civil Engineering. Today's date is

00:09.307 --> 00:12.792
July 22, 1981. Dr. McDonald, would you please tell 
us something about your boyhood years in

00:12.812 --> 00:23.146
Montgomery, Alabama?

00:23.166 --> 00:29.295
I grew up in Montgomery until I went to college. 
except for about three years that we lived in South

00:30.187 --> 00:36.355
Georgia in a couple of small towns there.

00:39.700 --> 00:47.010
My father was in the cottonseed oil business, and 
he was transferred to Georgia, and then we moved

00:39.700 --> 00:47.010
back later on. I went to the public schools there, 
mostly in Montgomery. During the war, my father

00:58.305 --> 00:59.907
was... I worked for a construction firm at Oak 
Ridge, and so he was away quite a good bit, and then

01:00.983 --> 01:11.055
moved back to Montgomery after the war was over. I 
continued there, living there until I graduated

01:12.797 --> 01:20.506
from high school, and then went to Auburn. When did 
you graduate from high school? In 1948. Went on to

01:26.493 --> 01:30.838
Auburn and took civil engineering there. 
graduated in May 1952 with a Bachelor of Civil

01:31.831 --> 01:36.658
Engineering degree. How did you develop an 
interest in engineering? It was most probably,

01:43.046 --> 01:45.870
there were several reasons. One is Auburn was a 
real strong engineering school and I had no real

01:46.031 --> 02:01.652
driving urge to be an engineer but I knew that was a 
good field and so I thought I would, I was

01:46.031 --> 02:01.652
considering that for quite a number of years but I 
had summertime jobs working with the city, the

02:02.932 --> 02:11.783
city engineer in Montgomery, and was assigned to a 
surveying crew. And over a period of several

02:11.823 --> 02:26.181
summers, I worked in various positions on a 
surveying crew, starting as a rodman and a

02:11.823 --> 02:26.181
chainman and instrument man and those things. And 
so I became very familiar with surveying. And like

02:30.085 --> 02:31.487
so many people, I thought that that was what civil 
engineering was, and it was kind of fun. I enjoyed

02:37.825 --> 02:38.345
it. Of course, I found out that civil engineering 
is a lot broader than that as I got into it, but I

02:39.827 --> 02:46.936
don't regret that. It's just that I got in sort of 
the back door. I think a lot of people do that.

02:54.326 --> 02:56.889
How was your family affected by the Depression? Do 
you remember anything about that? I don't have all

03:00.233 --> 03:01.575
that. depression baggage hanging over me. I was 
born in 1930. And of course, we went into the

03:05.954 --> 03:12.921
Depression or were just going into the Depression 
right then. But I always remember we had a house and

03:13.782 --> 03:21.309
lived a relatively comfortable life. We were not 
wealthy by any means. My father was a salary

03:24.332 --> 03:25.913
employee. But he was never out of work. And my 
mother did not work at that time and didn't have to.

03:36.656 --> 03:42.203
So I really don't have any recollections of that. I 
guess when we moved to Georgia, that might have

03:42.243 --> 03:47.189
been part of the job scene. I really don't 
remember. But I didn't come out of that with any

03:49.492 --> 03:54.618
terrible memories by any means. What about 
brothers and sisters? I have one brother who lives

03:57.766 --> 03:59.529
in Montgomery. He's a little bit older than I am. 
He's an investment banker there. He's lived there

04:04.476 --> 04:12.027
all his life except for college and the service.

04:12.047 --> 04:15.091
After you completed your bachelor's at Auburn, 
what did you do then? I was in ROTC at Auburn. And in

04:19.177 --> 04:22.161
1952, the Korean War was going on. So everyone who 
got a commission in the ROTC had to go to the

04:27.263 --> 04:35.533
service, so I went to the Air Force and spent three 
or four months in this country. I went in August of

04:37.055 --> 04:56.038
52 and spent some time at Fort Benning, Georgia and 
Langley Field, Virginia, and then was sent to

04:37.055 --> 04:56.038
Korea in, I believe it was April of 53, in early 
1953, and was there for one year. Came back, and

04:57.200 --> 05:01.767
then when I got back, I was discharged after 20 
months. In this interim, the Korean War, the

05:02.788 --> 05:06.153
truce, I guess, was signed. So all of a sudden, they 
had a need for no, certainly a less need for people

05:06.193 --> 05:14.786
in my category, so they mustered out a bunch of us. 
And I went to work for the highway department in

05:15.747 --> 05:23.679
Montgomery and spent another year and a half or so 
there. When did you go to work for the highway

05:24.159 --> 05:26.683
department? Just after I got out of the service. It 
must have been the summer of 53

05:29.483 --> 05:37.371
or 54, I guess. Summer of 54. And how long did you 
hold that position? Well, I stayed there. I was

05:44.078 --> 05:57.092
what was called a bridge design engineer and so I 
worked on designing bridges and enjoyed it for

05:44.078 --> 05:57.092
about six months and then found out I was repeating 
myself lost its interest. So I decided to go back to

06:00.188 --> 06:01.970
graduate school. And so I worked until the fall of 
1955. And in the meantime, of course, I'd applied

06:06.814 --> 06:11.058
for graduate school and been accepted. And so I 
went to graduate school in September of 55. Where?

06:15.882 --> 06:18.144
University of Illinois in Urbana-Champaign. And 
you completed your master's work there? Yes, in

06:21.207 --> 06:24.449
1957 and PhD in 1959. What was the topic of your 
dissertation? The topic was a numerical study of

06:28.342 --> 06:35.648
the vibrations of spherical shells. The 
motivation was the

06:37.130 --> 06:57.167
behavior of shell structures under dynamic 
loading, such as blasts, and primarily blasts

06:37.130 --> 06:57.167
that were sponsored by the Air Force, 
earthquakes, any sort of dynamic load that might

06:58.362 --> 07:00.044
strike a structure. And the particular 
structures I was interested in was spherical

07:00.064 --> 07:02.506
shells. So I did a computer study of the vibration 
characteristics and then did a little bit on what

07:02.526 --> 07:15.700
happens if a particular kind of blast pulse 
impacts on a spherical structure. It was one of the

07:17.061 --> 07:24.509
earlier digital

07:17.061 --> 07:24.509
computer studies of structures. This was when the 
computer business was just beginning. And

07:29.243 --> 07:34.329
Illinois had a homemade computer that was one of 
the pioneers. Not the pioneer, obviously, but one

07:34.429 --> 07:38.194
of the earlier of this kind of computer. So I did use 
that to do the calculations for my thesis.

07:48.146 --> 07:49.127
What about your family? I married. I have three 
children. When did you marry? In 1960.

07:58.657 --> 08:15.137
And I have three children, a boy who will be a 
freshman at the University of Texas next fall in

07:58.657 --> 08:15.137
September, a girl who will be a senior at Bryan High 
in September, and a 12-year-old who will be in the

07:58.657 --> 08:15.137
seventh grade at St. Michael's Academy.

08:17.660 --> 08:19.362
Where is your wife originally from? She's from 
California, Southern California. After you got

08:23.367 --> 08:28.073
your doctorate in 1959, what did you do then? and 
went to work for Lockheed Aircraft Corporation in

08:28.576 --> 08:35.244
Sunnyvale, California. They were just 
beginning, well, they were in the early stages of

08:35.264 --> 08:50.102
getting the missile and space satellite 
business, and I went to work in the space satellite

08:35.264 --> 08:50.102
part of what later became the Lockheed Missiles 
and Space Company. It's in, as I say, in Sunnyvale,

08:51.123 --> 08:55.208
which now is called Silicon Valley as well, that 
activities going on in microcomputer chips and

08:56.656 --> 08:59.780
that kind of thing. That of course was not, that 
wasn't even on the horizon I don't think at that

08:59.960 --> 09:04.285
time. I worked in structural dynamics for them and 
stayed there three years. That's where I met my

09:10.992 --> 09:15.257
wife and we were married as I say in 1960.

09:19.001 --> 09:24.047
When I was there I lived in Saratoga which is a 
small, was at the time a small community

09:25.495 --> 09:27.337
just on the outskirts of San Jose. Of course, the 
whole place has been paved now. The whole valley is

09:30.141 --> 09:33.886
completely changed. In 1962, you left Lockheed. 
Where did you go then? Went to Raleigh, North

09:38.332 --> 09:39.674
Carolina. I got a job as an assistant professor at 
North Carolina State in civil engineering. And so

09:49.487 --> 09:54.253
we moved to Raleigh in August of 62, and I started 
teaching. in September. And how long did you hold

09:57.231 --> 09:59.274
that position? I was assistant professor until, I 
believe it was three years, and then was promoted

09:59.294 --> 10:14.374
to associate professor, and stayed there two more 
years,

09:59.294 --> 10:14.374
and then left NC State. And I got tenure and all 
that, and I got promoted. Well, those two things

10:18.820 --> 10:21.844
were simultaneous, tenure and promotion. So I 
left in 67 and went back to work for Lockheed again,

10:23.157 --> 10:31.366
but this time as a department manager at a research 
center in Huntsville, Alabama. They were working

10:31.386 --> 10:36.192
with NASA in the space program primarily. And I was 
the manager of the structures department there.

10:42.058 --> 10:44.141
And you stayed there from 67 to when? Till 72. Well,

10:45.662 --> 10:52.590
late 72. become a little bit disenchanted with 
industry. And Lockheed wanted to transfer me back

10:57.002 --> 11:04.633
to California, and I didn't want to do that, nor did 
my family want to move back there. And I had thought

11:04.853 --> 11:09.299
perhaps the educational game was where I would be 
anyhow. I had met the department head, Dr. Sampson

11:10.660 --> 11:18.551
was department head at that time, and I knew him 
from professional activities, professional

11:10.660 --> 11:18.551
organizations. So I called him to see what the seen 
in academia was. And so that initial call led to my

11:26.455 --> 11:29.720
coming down here. And you came here in 1973? Yeah, 
January 1973. As an instructor, I mean as a

11:34.347 --> 11:37.351
professor in civil engineering? Yes. Okay, and 
how long were you a professor of civil

11:39.374 --> 11:42.979
engineering? Well, I still am, so eight and a half 
years, I guess. You became department head in

11:48.606 --> 11:50.369
1979? Yes, August the 1st was when I started. What 
are some of your duties here as department head?

11:58.805 --> 12:09.838
Well, I guess it's like any other department head 
to administer the affairs of the department, the

11:58.805 --> 12:09.838
fiscal and the personnel and the academic 
program. Obviously, any department,

12:10.719 --> 12:21.032
particularly one this size, one can't do that 
alone and shouldn't do that, shouldn't try to do

12:10.719 --> 12:21.032
that. But I'm responsible for coordinating all of 
those activities in the department, reporting to

12:22.312 --> 12:28.480
the dean of engineering.

12:31.404 --> 12:36.651
About how many faculty members are there in the 
civil engineering department? We have

12:36.671 --> 12:42.319
several, 65 to 70. I forget the specific number of 
people who are in either tenure track or tenured

12:42.379 --> 12:49.829
positions, assistant professor and above. In 
addition to those, we have have something like a

12:52.501 --> 12:56.768
dozen or so people in lecturer positions. 
Totally, though, each of the two major semesters

12:58.591 --> 13:09.508
will have something like 100 people involved in 
the teaching program if you add in teaching

12:58.591 --> 13:09.508
assistants and then the lecturers into the 
regular faculty. Oh, well, I shouldn't say it that

13:11.190 --> 13:12.733
way. Teaching assistants into the faculty. 
Certainly, I did not mean to exclude lecturers

13:15.036 --> 13:18.762
from faculty.

13:21.273 --> 13:23.836
What are some of the schools that these faculty 
members are from? We have them from all over. We

13:27.201 --> 13:29.524
have several, of course, from A&M. I'd say a fairly 
large number from A&M, but we have people from the

13:31.867 --> 13:46.386
University of Illinois, the University of 
California at Berkeley, University of Texas,

13:31.867 --> 13:46.386
Texas Tech,

13:31.867 --> 13:46.386
just about Well, I won't say all over, but 
certainly representative throughout the

13:47.986 --> 13:51.471
country.

13:54.876 --> 14:03.869
Probably those I named,

13:54.876 --> 14:03.869
I would say the preponderance of people with 
advanced degrees got them in those schools. But

14:03.889 --> 14:06.533
certainly there are a lot of them. Are faculty 
members expected to devote time between research

14:08.596 --> 14:13.183
and teaching? Yes, most of the faculty in the 
department are involved in one way or another in

14:14.767 --> 14:19.934
the research program. Could you explain more 
about the research program?

14:31.451 --> 14:38.901
The faculty members in the CE department work in 
every conceivable field almost in research. and

14:39.607 --> 14:45.376
what is generally called civil engineering, and 
some things which are not normally considered to

14:39.607 --> 14:45.376
be classical civil engineering. Most of our 
research is administered in either the Texas

14:46.878 --> 14:56.072
Engineering Experiment Station or the Texas 
Transportation Institute.

14:58.676 --> 15:06.829
In fact, the faculty members will hold a joint 
appointment with those two state agencies, as

14:58.676 --> 15:06.829
well as an appointment as, say, a professor or 
whatever. with the university in the civil

15:07.265 --> 15:12.774
engineering department.

15:12.794 --> 15:18.884
We like to encourage the faculty to do research and 
also to publish the results of their research. We

15:19.886 --> 15:25.735
feel that that's just one more service in teaching 
that we have, one more function that we should

15:19.886 --> 15:25.735
perform. It's involved and intimately involved 
with our teaching, actually, particularly with

15:27.158 --> 15:33.508
the graduate teaching program. Could you discuss 
specifically some of the research projects that

15:35.935 --> 15:42.243
are underway now or have been completed in the last 
several years? Well, that would take all day, but

15:43.965 --> 16:02.770
one of the larger projects and one of the important 
ones, I think, is an environmental impact of the

15:43.965 --> 16:02.770
Strategic Petroleum Reserve that our 
Environmental Engineering Division is involved

15:43.965 --> 16:02.770
in. The Strategic Petroleum Reserve is a program 
by the federal government to store large

16:04.657 --> 16:18.509
quantities of petroleum oil in very large salt 
domes. Salt domes are subterranean, and they're

16:18.549 --> 16:23.413
extremely stable. Well, to put the oil in, you have 
to pump the brine out. And so what the government

16:29.078 --> 16:33.162
will be doing is depositing high concentrations 
of brine in the Gulf of Mexico as the oil displaces

16:33.580 --> 16:40.307
the brine from the dome. The government obviously 
wanted to know what the environmental impact of

16:42.930 --> 16:49.437
that large slug of brine would be. So we're really 
program managers of a multidisciplinary program

16:49.597 --> 17:02.912
involving scientists and oceanographers and 
biologists as well as engineers. instrumenting

17:03.398 --> 17:07.724
and monitoring the impact of this brine. Another 
program is a program with the Air Force. The Air

17:16.715 --> 17:29.271
Force is interested in people who, well, in two 
things, in developing the general field of the use

17:16.715 --> 17:29.271
of composite materials and also in educating 
engineers who are knowledgeable in design and use

17:30.314 --> 17:33.097
of composite materials. So we have a program 
sponsored by the Air Force that's both education

17:33.117 --> 17:51.379
and teaching, and a classroom education, that 
kind of education as opposed to research, in which

17:33.117 --> 17:51.379
the faculty carry out a research program in the use 
and manufacturing, design, and so on, of

17:33.117 --> 17:51.379
composite materials. And I also conduct a degree 
program so that people with BS degrees in

17:52.380 --> 17:59.629
engineering can come here, study for a year, and 
get master's degrees in some field of

18:00.098 --> 18:17.482
engineering, but with the emphasis on the design 
and use of composite materials so they can now

18:00.098 --> 18:17.482
return to the aircraft industry and apply these 
newly discovered skills to the use of composite.

18:17.502 --> 18:26.815
Composite materials are sort of, in one sense, the 
wave of the future in structural design in certain

18:17.502 --> 18:26.815
applications because of a very high strength to 
weight ratio. And naturally, if you can have

18:29.368 --> 18:33.712
something very strong that doesn't weigh very 
much, then the aircraft people are interested in

18:29.368 --> 18:33.712
it. But now, of course, there's more and more 
interest in the automotive industry and the

18:34.793 --> 18:41.080
application of composites. Because if you save a 
pound of weight in an automobile, that's a certain

18:41.180 --> 18:51.831
amount of savings in gasoline that you don't have 
to spend to push that pound around the road. Let's

18:54.314 --> 18:57.257
see, there are other programs.

18:59.414 --> 19:12.527
We've had programs in the study of the

18:59.414 --> 19:12.527
behavior of subsurface, well, the ocean bottom. 
It turns out that in certain areas of the Gulf, the

19:12.547 --> 19:23.337
ocean bottom is a very uncohesive material. And 
due to the wave action in storms, the wave action

19:29.367 --> 19:35.956
can trigger huge slides, mudslides, as it were, on 
the bottom of the ocean. Even though the slopes of

19:37.017 --> 19:48.593
the ocean bottom are not very large, the material 
is so uncohesive that it won't stick together,

19:37.017 --> 19:48.593
that it'll move under these high pressures. 
Naturally, the oil companies or the companies who

19:49.734 --> 19:57.585
have that drilling are very interested in that 
because if the whole floor of the ocean starts

19:49.734 --> 19:57.585
moving, there's not a lot that, Well, it certainly 
has an impact on the drilling rig, drilling

19:58.763 --> 20:02.967
platforms. So we, in the geotechnical 
engineering division, have been studying the

20:02.987 --> 20:21.224
effect of these mudslides and the forces 
generated by the mudslides so that we can then take

20:02.987 --> 20:21.224
their results and see what the impact on the 
drilling rigs would be. And then the next obvious

20:21.624 --> 20:27.690
question is what procedures or how can we design 
the... drilling rigs to resist these very large

20:28.970 --> 20:33.215
forces that are generated by these slides. You 
could go on and on. Basically, this might add a

20:38.981 --> 20:52.436
little to this, basically we have, the civil 
engineering department has six groups, we call

20:38.981 --> 20:52.436
them, major areas, major administrative 
subdivisions. These are ocean and coastal

20:52.456 --> 20:58.723
engineering, environmental engineering, 
structures, construction and materials,

20:59.952 --> 21:13.569
geotechnical, or I guess we call it 
geoengineering, and civil systems engineering.

21:15.472 --> 21:21.439
If you look at the details of this, this covers 
pretty much the broad spectrum of civil

21:15.472 --> 21:21.439
engineering activity. And we have a research 
program in every one of those areas covering many

21:22.381 --> 21:29.790
facets of the business.

21:33.398 --> 21:37.444
Could you explain briefly in layman's terms what a 
civil engineer does? The layman's term is not the

21:39.327 --> 21:42.191
problem. The problem is the breadth of the field. I 
guess this is very simplistic, but in a sense,

21:46.116 --> 22:02.460
civil engineers are the people who design, 
construct, maintain, and run the machinery of

21:46.116 --> 22:02.460
civilization. By this, I mean all those things, 
those engineered works that are basic to running

22:02.609 --> 22:31.873
the civilization, the transportation network, 
the water supply,

22:02.609 --> 22:31.873
disposing of the waste, constructing the 
buildings, designing the facility, designing

22:02.609 --> 22:31.873
the bridges, designing and supervising 
construction of the

22:34.486 --> 22:43.780
all the appurtenances and all the buildings that 
go along with all these things, the sewer plants

22:34.486 --> 22:43.780
and such, maintaining all of these, developing 
new materials. We have a big program, for example,

22:44.381 --> 23:00.105
in the Texas Transportation Institute in the 
development of asphaltic materials that would be

22:44.381 --> 23:00.105
used in highways and other parking lots and other 
things where they use large volumes of asphalt

22:44.381 --> 23:00.105
paving.

23:03.207 --> 23:16.382
Involving all of this, of course, would be the 
economic studies as to determine the best

23:03.207 --> 23:16.382
approach, where to locate the facilities, what's 
the best way. And by that, I mean the most, say,

23:16.402 --> 23:23.190
cost-effective way to design them and to 
construct them. So the economics of the matter, as

23:23.210 --> 23:29.738
in all engineering, really, the economics of the 
matter gets into it very, very heavily. But

23:31.709 --> 23:33.332
there's really no limit. That's kind of classical 
civil engineering. But if you look at where our

23:36.617 --> 23:47.356
graduates go, a large percentage, a significant 
percentage, I don't know the figure, but a

23:36.617 --> 23:47.356
significant percentage of our students go to work 
for the oil companies. Well, obviously, because

23:47.816 --> 23:50.882
here in Texas, that's a very important industry. 
And they're hiring people with technical

23:50.902 --> 23:53.987
backgrounds.

23:57.005 --> 24:01.673
How many hours does it take to get the bachelor's 
degree here in civil engineering? Semester

24:01.693 --> 24:02.334
hours? It takes 146 in our current program. And how 
many for the master's and PhD?

24:11.369 --> 24:12.571
It gets a little less rigid. There's a specified 
curriculum in the undergraduate program. I

24:17.839 --> 24:20.223
believe it's 16 hours, no more than that. 16 hours 
of technical electives, but then we have some

24:20.584 --> 24:23.248
other electives. total of about 25 hours of 
electives. But it all adds up to 146. For the master

24:30.262 --> 24:36.410
of engineering degree, the minimum is 36 hours. 
But there, you look a little more closely at a

24:36.510 --> 24:42.237
person's background and interest. Where does the 
student want to go when he finishes here? And what

24:45.841 --> 24:48.424
kind of work does he want to get into? And you might 
require a few more hours, just depending on the

24:53.823 --> 24:55.966
background, what he's had, and so on. The master of 
science degree requires 32 hours, but of course,

24:56.647 --> 25:01.153
you have to write a thesis. We require a thesis for 
the master of science degree.

25:06.101 --> 25:13.972
The PhD, for the PhD, the graduate college 
requires a minimum of 96 after the bachelor's

25:06.101 --> 25:13.972
degree. Again, if it's appropriate, we'll 
require more than that. That's a minimum

25:18.698 --> 25:19.780
requirement. And of course, a significant maybe 
25% or 30% of those hours, depending on the

25:21.683 --> 25:30.275
student, would be taken up with this 
dissertation. Now, that's about right. Usually,

25:33.639 --> 25:37.985
we'll give maybe 20 credits for the dissertation, 
20 semester hours. But those are only minimum

25:38.005 --> 25:40.228
requirements. And if it's appropriate, we'll go 
over that. About how many students are now

25:42.972 --> 25:46.016
enrolled in civil engineering here? Last fall, we 
had

25:52.818 --> 26:08.555
something like 850,

25:52.818 --> 26:08.555
I believe was the figure, undergraduate in civil 
and 115

25:52.818 --> 26:08.555
undergraduates in the ocean engineering 
program, which is a degree program in civil

25:52.818 --> 26:08.555
engineering department. And on top of that, 150 
graduate students. All those figures probably

26:15.403 --> 26:22.791
don't add up, but it added up to around 1,200 
students, undergraduates as well as graduates in

26:15.403 --> 26:22.791
both civil and ocean engineering. Do you have any 
women students in civil engineering? Yes, that's

26:31.304 --> 26:33.427
another interesting thing. I think this is a 
national observation too, but it seems that that

26:33.467 --> 26:39.516
percentage is rising. We've had on the order of 
about 12% of our undergraduate student body has

26:39.596 --> 26:45.865
been women over the past several years. That seems 
to be going up a little bit. I think with this coming

26:48.289 --> 26:51.934
fall enrollment, we'll probably see an increase. 
Certainly a trend of increasing the number of the

26:52.724 --> 26:59.275
percent of the female, of students that are 
female. What about black students in

26:59.695 --> 27:03.241
engineering? We don't have very many. That's a 
very difficult problem. We've had them.

27:07.548 --> 27:12.176
Certainly we would love to have more, but we don't 
have very many right now. We do have some. Why do you

27:13.518 --> 27:16.062
think you have so few blacks in engineering? I 
don't know. The only thing, whatever I would say

