don't have that. I mean, I have the number. I just 
don't have it right before me. I would say...

31:06.170 --> 31:20.247
probably in the order total again comparing that 
1200 figure on the order of six or 800, something

31:06.170 --> 31:20.247
like that.

31:20.267 --> 31:23.751
How does civil engineers compare to other 
engineers in salary ranges? That's a changing

31:25.574 --> 31:27.055
thing. And also the impact over the past two years 
of The demand for petroleum engineers and

31:33.001 --> 31:37.588
chemical engineers have just changed the picture 
completely. But two years ago, I would have

31:37.628 --> 31:54.775
answered that civil engineers probably run a 
little behind mechanicals and electricals and

31:37.628 --> 31:54.775
petroleum or chemicals, perhaps, but ahead of 
aerospace and some of the others. That's

31:56.378 --> 31:58.781
changing, and it will probably change. I know it 
will change in the future, for example, if the

32:01.807 --> 32:09.116
government goes ahead with the large defense 
program, that will impact the demand for

32:01.807 --> 32:09.116
aerospace engineers. So the whole thing will 
change. Some of the petroleum engineers, the

32:10.818 --> 32:19.949
salaries for the graduates of petroleum 
engineers are something that we would not have

32:10.818 --> 32:19.949
dreamed of even two or three years ago. We're 
probably average or a little below, though, if you

32:22.092 --> 32:27.579
take out all those extreme data points. I wouldn't 
say it's enough. I personally would not think it's

32:30.764 --> 32:35.292
enough to impact anyone's career decision. It's 
not that significant.

32:40.261 --> 32:48.014
Do you have any idea on how the civil engineering 
program at Texas A&M ranks with programs at other

32:40.261 --> 32:48.014
universities? No, you see figures on those things 
and sometimes we appear in the ratings and

32:48.034 --> 32:53.464
sometimes we don't. I'm very skeptical of those. I 
guess if A&M's civil engineering department

32:55.667 --> 33:01.154
always came in at number one, I'd say they were very 
accurate. But nevertheless, it's terribly hard

33:01.814 --> 33:07.641
for me to see what those ratings mean. When you say 
the best, I don't know what the terms are. I believe

33:13.288 --> 33:23.620
quite often that the way those ratings are made, 
what they're really relating is the current

33:24.207 --> 33:37.441
gossip among academicians,

33:24.207 --> 33:37.441
and also probably more heavily reflective of the 
graduate program, because that's really where

33:24.207 --> 33:37.441
publicity comes quite often. But the only thing I 
can say, I guess we have shown up in those, and we've

33:38.823 --> 33:43.448
not shown up in others. But certainly, I 
personally think we're in the top 20. But that's,

33:49.334 --> 33:50.856
again, a subjective judgment.

33:56.472 --> 34:01.579
What are some of the changes that you've seen since 
you came here eight years ago, in those eight

33:56.472 --> 34:01.579
years? Regarding what? Regarding civil 
engineering. In the department? Well, certainly

34:05.564 --> 34:09.049
increasing the number of students, increasing 
the faculty. We now have been able to attract

34:10.811 --> 34:22.547
several young, very, very promising assistant 
professors.

34:24.063 --> 34:33.594
I think as time goes on,

34:24.063 --> 34:33.594
the department will tend to get, and in fact right 
now, is tending to get a little younger. Not that we

34:34.555 --> 34:40.562
are terribly old in the sense of the faculty 
department by any means, but there are some people

34:34.555 --> 34:40.562
retiring. And because of the increasing number of 
students we have, we've had positions and have

34:41.683 --> 34:48.271
been able to fill them with younger people. I think 
the department is becoming more oriented towards

34:53.560 --> 34:59.928
research, though I'm convinced not to the 
detriment of our teaching program. We have not

35:01.029 --> 35:06.295
changed there on our feelings of the importance of 
the undergraduate teaching program. I think we

35:07.557 --> 35:19.411
feel that we can continue to have a strong 
undergraduate teaching program in spite of a

35:07.557 --> 35:19.411
growing and changing, to a certain extent, 
changing research program. The facilities have

35:20.713 --> 35:23.196
not changed. That's one of our problems, but 
there's some light on the horizon as far as our

35:23.800 --> 35:30.387
facilities are concerned. We're getting more 
office space. We're going to have available in a

35:33.651 --> 35:38.776
couple of years a graduate research laboratory. I 
guess I'm telling you what we'd like to see change

35:41.078 --> 35:51.850
rather than what I have seen change, but we'd like 
to see improvement in our undergraduate teaching

35:41.078 --> 35:51.850
laboratories, which We're in very bad shape 
there. The curriculum has changed. The

35:59.438 --> 36:02.881
curriculum, as I said earlier, has reached 146 
semester hours. That's gone up over the past. In

36:06.404 --> 36:08.066
fact, that went up just two years ago.

36:11.469 --> 36:13.931
The topics covered in the curriculum have 
changed. We think that our curriculum, as far as

36:15.032 --> 36:22.039
the topics covered, is probably about as broad and 
also as modern as any in the country. We have not

36:25.345 --> 36:29.850
responded to fads so much as other places have. So 
the changes, I think, that we've made in the

36:30.971 --> 36:34.515
curriculum have been very positive changes.

36:37.758 --> 36:40.681
What are some of the fads that other colleges have 
changed? Well, during the post-Sputnik era, so

36:41.262 --> 36:50.271
many engineering colleges became colleges of 
engineering science. I can't take any credit for

36:51.685 --> 37:21.625
resisting that because I was not here but A&M by and 
large resisted that keeping in mind that

36:51.685 --> 37:21.625
engineering is a profession and that engineers 
are charged with the actual design and

36:51.685 --> 37:21.625
implementation not just analysis of various 
things engineering works and so we have continued

36:51.685 --> 37:21.625
to have a very practical bent that is where we want 
our graduates to be able to go out, A&M, and

37:22.111 --> 37:34.469
actually take responsible charge of the design 
and construction of engineered works. Some of the

37:35.831 --> 37:43.642
other schools, I believe, became more, also with 
the advent of computers, became more heavily

37:35.831 --> 37:43.642
analytically oriented. And there are students in 
some of these places that students really are not

37:45.325 --> 37:51.173
prepared to function as engineers, in my 
judgment. as well as ours are. Have you seen a

37:54.627 --> 37:59.774
change in the quality of the student entering 
civil engineering in the last eight years? I think

38:01.717 --> 38:04.080
so. In fact, I think in even a shorter period of time 
than that, the quality has gone up. Now, I could be

38:12.231 --> 38:20.181
just reacting or reflecting various scores that 
I've seen, the average SAT score, for example, for

38:20.549 --> 38:28.159
entering engineering students is now, I believe 
this is right, is the highest of any of the colleges

38:20.549 --> 38:28.159
at A&M. That's a change from the past several 
years. With my own classroom teaching, the

38:31.022 --> 38:41.736
students are, I believe, are better as students, 
reflecting also a national trend, I think. The

38:41.856 --> 38:50.387
students are much more interested in getting 
useful and much more pragmatic. They want to learn

38:53.732 --> 39:01.979
things in the classroom where they can see a direct 
use, a direct application when they get out of

38:53.732 --> 39:01.979
here. I personally think that's something the 
faculty have to resist. It's impossible, I think,

39:08.565 --> 39:13.649
to identify any practical use with everything 
that you do. I think what we have to do is educate

39:14.650 --> 39:21.336
them as well as we see fit to be good, broad, solid 
practicing engineers. But the students are, I

39:24.860 --> 39:28.625
believe, much more pragmatic than they were 
several years ago. But I believe they're better

39:29.165 --> 39:30.367
students. They certainly seem to want to get on 
with the program, as it were. Of course, they're

39:35.694 --> 39:37.115
always the exception. Well, that would seem a 
conflict that general apparent prevailing

39:37.135 --> 39:45.606
public opinion that the quality of students is 
decreasing. We have pretty high admission

39:45.626 --> 39:47.429
standards. And A&M has high admission standards. 
Engineering tends to get those students who, of

39:52.147 --> 40:05.424
course, are interested in and thereby probably 
more proficient than average in technical

39:52.147 --> 40:05.424
subjects, mathematics and science and so on. But I 
believe that all my colleagues have told me the

40:06.385 --> 40:14.315
same thing, at least the ones with whom I've 
discussed this. But I think that the quality of

40:15.016 --> 40:19.842
students that we're getting in this college and 
this department is generally tending to

40:15.016 --> 40:19.842
increase.

40:24.563 --> 40:26.165
I said one thing about the women students. The 
women students, the early women students, again,

40:27.107 --> 40:36.820
this is a subjective reaction, were better on 
average than the men students. We had some

40:38.062 --> 40:41.907
outstanding, and still do, we had outstanding 
women students. As more and more women enter the

40:41.927 --> 40:52.562
program, though, I think, as you would expect, 
they seem to be about as good, but not any better or

40:41.927 --> 40:52.562
any worse than the average male student. Many 
grades and all that would support that. I don't

40:54.823 --> 40:55.163
know. Again, that's a subjective judgment. Do you 
have any figures on what percent of the students

40:57.886 --> 41:03.654
who start a program in civil engineering finally 
finish the master's degree? No, I don't. We could

41:06.077 --> 41:06.738
get those. I just don't remember what they are. We 
do have a kind of peculiar, what I think is

41:08.921 --> 41:12.385
peculiar, anomaly.

41:15.089 --> 41:22.178
Most of the time, when you think of a four-year 
curriculum, you think, at least I would think

41:15.089 --> 41:22.178
normally, that the largest group would be the 
freshmen. the next largest the sophomores, and so

41:22.495 --> 41:24.677
on down. That's not the case here. The largest 
group we have are the seniors. We're just almost

41:29.042 --> 41:30.964
completely reversed. Our freshman class tends to 
be smaller than the sophomore, which tends to be,

41:32.005 --> 41:40.633
although there are exceptions, than the junior, 
and the senior being the largest of them all. We get

41:41.675 --> 41:48.081
a lot of transfers, students who started in other 
fields of engineering at A&M, and also students

41:41.675 --> 41:48.081
who go to the first two or three years at other 
colleges and then transfer in. So the transfers

41:54.615 --> 42:03.124
tend to swell our upper division classes as 
compared to the freshmen. We don't have a large

42:04.405 --> 42:07.088
attrition rate, though, I don't believe. We lose 
some, of course, but we don't lose a lot of students

42:07.148 --> 42:13.094
to just flunking out. I mean, with a freshman class 
in the top quarter of their high school class, And

42:18.959 --> 42:25.650
good SAT scores, you wouldn't expect to lose a big 
bunch. Do you have any notion of what that average

42:25.670 --> 42:31.639
SAT score is for people in this program? Not in 
civil. In engineering, it was, I believe it was the

42:32.200 --> 42:35.626
last fall, it was on the order. It was between 1050 
and 1100. I forget the figures. I don't want to

42:39.752 --> 42:40.714
quote a wrong figure. I believe it was around 1070. 
I'm just trying to drag that up from my memory, but

42:43.765 --> 42:46.869
it was on that order. I do remember, though, it was 
the highest of all the colleges A&M. It was the

42:50.354 --> 42:51.195
highest average. That's on which test? That's the 
SAT. I thought the SAT used a scale of 1 through 30.

42:57.303 --> 42:57.563
No. They must have changed their scale. They quote 
them in, it's an arbitrary scale, but as I

42:59.726 --> 43:11.361
remember, 1,000, a total of 1,000, is real close to 
the 50th percentile. Could you tell us briefly,

43:13.263 --> 43:19.011
what the future outlook of civil engineers for the 
80s would be in your judgment? I think it looks

43:19.031 --> 43:19.832
good. I think all engineering looks good. Civil 
engineering has the trend, the tendency, is for it

43:22.816 --> 43:39.658
to follow the population, if nothing else, 
because as the population expands, we have a

43:22.816 --> 43:39.658
greater need for all those things that support the 
population, transportation and sanitary.

43:42.682 --> 43:42.882
But Even now, I was told the other day that if you 
compare new student acceptances for the fall, the

43:43.435 --> 43:58.757
first of June figures, compare new student 
acceptances for the fall with the same figures for

43:43.435 --> 43:58.757
last year, we're up 9%. This kind of just continues 
the trend that's been going on for years. We've

44:06.167 --> 44:07.549
been growing. The civil engineering enrollment 
here has been growing more or less linearly. with

44:12.325 --> 44:15.848
some wiggles in the lines, of course, but more or 
less linearly for the last decade. I think that

44:17.950 --> 44:20.993
that shows all signs of continuing. Certainly, 
the demand for civil engineers is probably going

44:21.033 --> 44:25.217
to continue. Also, the fact that civil 
engineering here, at least, the civil

44:27.159 --> 44:38.670
engineering graduates have a pretty broad 
education, that is something that a lot of the

44:39.494 --> 44:42.858
major companies want, the major oil companies, 
for example. If they can't hire petroleum

44:42.878 --> 44:47.322
engineers, they're happy with civils or 
mechanicals. And so there's a demand there for

44:47.683 --> 44:55.511
civil engineers in what's considered not to be a 
classical civil engineering field. So I'd say

44:56.552 --> 45:00.336
that the 80s look good. In fact, if you look at the 
demographics, there might be a small drop in

45:00.516 --> 45:09.045
availability of high school students, certainly 
a small drop nationally an even smaller drop in

45:09.363 --> 45:17.054
Texas of people graduating from high schools who 
would be going to college next. So if anything,

45:18.176 --> 45:38.104
that might mean, from a demand point of view, that 
if the demand continues to rise and then there is a

45:18.176 --> 45:38.104
smaller group of people who are going to be going 
through the colleges, that those people who do go

45:18.176 --> 45:38.104
through the colleges in engineering are going to 
have even better job opportunities, I'd say. I

45:38.759 --> 45:40.020
know it's somewhat contradictory. I'm not really 
even sure that that's going to affect our

45:40.040 --> 45:44.085
enrollments. The drop in the number of high school 
students from the figures I've seen at least seem

45:44.285 --> 45:51.814
to be fairly small in Texas. But I'd say that just 
generally as a career that it will probably

45:51.834 --> 45:59.322
continue to be good. We're less subject to some of 
the fluctuations of some of the other

45:59.722 --> 46:05.529
engineering. For example, the aerospace 
industry. tend to be much more, to fluctuate much

46:08.746 --> 46:12.873
more than civil engineering. Well, aerospace 
industry was in a slump for many years in the 70s,

46:12.893 --> 46:16.579
wasn't it? Yes, sure was. And it's just now 
beginning to climb up out of that. Petroleum

46:20.225 --> 46:25.754
engineers, you had a very difficult time getting 
petroleum engineering graduates jobs a while

46:20.225 --> 46:25.754
back. But now, of course, it's just the sky's the 
limit.

